January is National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month. Human trafficking is modern-day slavery and affects people in every corner of our nation and beyond, too often as a result of our porous borders.  The Department of Homeland Security created the Blue Campaign in 2010 as a public awareness tool to inform Americans on the signs of human trafficking. The Blue Campaign also provides training to law enforcement, government agencies, and private companies on ways to detect victims and report incidents of human trafficking. Learn more about the Blue Campaign and what DHS is doing to #EndTrafficking.

Here's the complete joint statement from Senators Graham, Cassidy, Heller & Johnson:  "As a result of our efforts in the last few weeks, it‚Äôs not a question of ‚Äòif‚Äô Graham-Cassidy-Heller-Johnson replaces Obamacare ‚Äì it‚Äôs only a question of ‚Äòwhen.‚Äô  Our approach ends the march towards single-payer health care where all medical decisions are made by a Washington bureaucrat.   ‚ÄúObamacare's problems are widespread and well known.  Forty five percent of counties or parishes in the U.S. are down to single provider. Premiums are skyrocketing.  And families across the country are suffering under the weight of this failed law.  Unfortunately, these problems will only get worse over time.    ‚ÄúDue to circumstances under our control and not under our control, the process and timing of this vote did not line up this time. However, our idea of sending the power and money to the states clearly resounded with our colleagues.  A one-size fits all approach to health care does not work.  The needs of South Carolina are different than those in Louisiana, Nevada, and Wisconsin.  Our system should be flexible to reflect this reality.  We can all say with confidence that our plan not only replaces Obamacare ‚Äì it will end the march led by our Democratic friends towards single-payer health care.   ‚ÄúWhile the arcane rules of the reconciliation process limited our policy options and imposed an artificial deadline on our efforts, we will push on.    ‚ÄúThe most frequent frustration we heard from our colleagues ranging from Senator McCain to Senator Murkowski was that time and process were the biggest obstacles to their support.  There is no doubt about their commitment to repeal and replace Obamacare and no doubt about their support of local control.   ‚ÄúWe have never felt better about the idea that we can now ‚Äì as a party ‚Äì not only repeal, but replace Obamacare with an idea that will pay off for the American health care consumer. Under our approach, the money and power in Washington is given to state officials who will be accountable at the ballot box and therefore more accessible than any Washington bureaucrat.   ‚ÄúIt is just a matter of time until we fulfill our promise to repeal and replace Obamacare with something far better.  For the American people, when it comes to Obamacare, the worst is yet to come.  That is why we believe Graham-Cassidy-Heller-Johnson is needed and will eventually pass.   ‚ÄúFinally, we truly appreciate the leadership and assistance shown by Leader McConnell and his leadership team, the President and Vice President.  They have all been fully engaged in this effort and we could not have come this far without their hard work.  We look forward to our continued collaboration in the days and weeks ahead.‚Äù

A big day for more effective government with the President signing the Dr. Chris Kirkpatrick Whistleblower Protection Act.  The bill is named after a whistleblower at the Tomah VA who took his own life after being fired for questioning excessive prescription practices at the facility. Dr. Kirkpatrick‚Äôs brother, Sean, testified at a Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee hearing about the retaliation his brother faced.  This bill is a direct result of Sen. Johnson's committee investigation. It also implements a number of suggestions that Sean Kirkpatrick and others have made to improve whistleblower protections at the VA and across the federal government. The legislation will strengthen penalties on those who retaliate against whistleblowers, add protections for probationary employees, and ensure that federal employees have a greater knowledge of whistleblower protections.
